        "Discharge Summary\n\nPatient Information:\n- Age: 29 years\n- Gender: Female\n- Allergy Status: No Known Allergies to Drugs (NKDA)\n- Discharge Disposition: Home\n- Discharge Diagnosis: L5/S1 disc tear and severe spinal stenosis\n\nChief Complaint and History of Present Illness:\nThe patient is a 29-year-old female with a history of lower back pain (LBP) since early 2011, which worsened significantly over the month prior to admission. The pain radiated down the back of her left leg and became unbearable, accompanied by left calf weakness and limited walking ability. Conservative management (ESI, Medrol, Neurontin, Oxycodone) had failed to provide relief.\n\nMedical and Family History:\n- Past Medical History: Rosacea, seasonal allergies, headache, and abnormal Pap smears.\n- Family History: Maternal grandmother with TIAs.\n\nDiagnostic Findings:\n- Physical Exam: Vital signs were stable. Neurological exam revealed 4+ motor strength in the left gastrocnemius (plantar flexion), with other muscle groups at 5/5. The left Achilles reflex was absent (0). Sensory exam showed decreased sensation along the left lateral calf to pinprick and temperature. Crucially, a rectal exam confirmed normal sphincter control (ruling out cauda equina syndrome).\n- MRI Lumbar Spine: Identified markedly severe L5-S1 discogenic disease with a 1 cm midline to left paracentral disc protrusion/partial extrusion causing significant spinal canal stenosis and nerve root impingement. Moderate L4-L5 degenerative disease with moderate neural foraminal narrowing was also noted.\n\nSurgical Intervention and Hospital Course:\nThe patient underwent a Left L5-S1 discectomy. The procedure was successful. Postoperatively, she was managed with Decadron for inflammation and transitioned to oral pain medications. Her recovery was uncomplicated; she achieved independent ambulation, her incision remained clean and dry, and her pain was well-controlled. \n\nDischarge Condition:\nThe patient was discharged in a stable condition, awake and alert. She exhibited trace residual left plantar flexion and dorsiflexion weakness with minor sensory loss on the lateral aspect of the foot. She was ambulatory and steady.\n\nDischarge Medications:\n- Pain Management: Oxycodone 5 mg (Q3H PRN), Gabapentin 100 mg (TID), Acetaminophen 325 mg (Q6H PRN), and Ibuprofen 400 mg (Q8H PRN).\n- Stool Softeners: Docusate Sodium 100 mg and Senna 8.6 mg (both BID).\n- Routine: Citalopram 20 mg (Daily).\n\nDischarge Instructions:\n- Activity: No smoking. No pulling, lifting >10 lbs, or excessive bending/twisting for two weeks. Limit use of stairs. Do not drive while taking narcotics.\n- Wound Care: Keep wound clean; no tub baths or pools until follow-up. Showers may begin after dressing removal.\n- Medication Note: While standard spine instructions advise against NSAIDs (Ibuprofen) for 3 months to promote bone fusion, this patient underwent a discectomy (not fusion), and Ibuprofen was explicitly listed in her discharge medications.\n- Follow-up: Scheduled with Neurosurgery.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
